<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12150d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12150d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12150d"> 150(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> V.F creates Catalan / question ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Creating the Catalan question is what Saint Vincent does, by insisting on separating and segregating the different ethnic and religious groups in Spain, the Moriscos (Moors), the Maranos (Jews) and the Christians]</font> <br>Que voyait donc ma&icirc;tre Vincent Ferrier lorsqu&apos;il contemplait le tumulte confus de la vie en cette vaste p&eacute;ninsule ib&eacute;rique? Un spectacle fort banal. Quelque chose de chaotique, de confus. D&apos;abord il y avait cinq &Eacute;tats, in&eacute;gaux, formidablement in&eacute;gaux. Dans les m&ecirc;mes villes et dans les m&ecirc;mes campagnes vivaient, plus ou moins p&ecirc;le-m&ecirc;le des Maures, des Juifs, des chr&eacute;tiens. Et ces chr&eacute;tiens eux-m&ecirc;mes formaient des peuples bien diff&eacute;rents souvent hostiles les uns aux autres: Gascons, Catalans, Castillans, Aragonais, Portugais, avaient chacun leur langue, leur pass&eacute;, leurs moeurs et diff&eacute;raient presque autant que peuvent diff&eacute;rer des Fran&ccedil;ais, des Anglais, des Allemands et des Italiens. Cependant ces chr&eacute;tiens, si divis&eacute;s entre eux, s&apos;unissaient dans une haine commune de l&apos;infid&egrave;le: maure ou juif. <br><font color="green">[What did master Vincent Ferrier see when he thought about the tumultuous life on that vast iberian peninsula? A really banal spectacle, chaotic and confused. First there were five States, unequal, incredibly unequal. In the same cities and the same countryside there lived, more or less helter-skelter, Moors, Jews, Christians. And these Christians belong to different, sometimes hostile peoples: Gascons, Catalonians, Castillians, Aragonians, Portuguese, they all had their own language, their own past, their habits and they were as different as the French, the English, the Germans and the Italians. Yet these Christians, divided among themselves as they were, were united in their common hatred for the infidel: the Moors and the Jews.]</font> <small> Matthieu-Maxime Gorce, <a name="STVF" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#STVF"><cite title="source">Saint Vincent Ferrier</cite></a> (1924) 234-5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c12154l" href="c12all.htm#c12154l">VI.C.12:154(l)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
